        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Basset. Southampton</placeName>
                    <date>Sept. 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I can give you very little information on your subject.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Earwigs are said, I believe—in Kirby &amp; Spence, to take charge of their young,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> &amp; I am sure that I have read that even Star-fishes do the same for their eggs, as everyone must have read of Spiders—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I rather think that I have referred to star-fishes in 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Edit. of Descent of Man.— Other fish, besides Stickle-backs, take charge of their young; of which I give fresh instances in 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Edit. of Descent.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Southampton] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10153.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 7 September [1875]</ref>, Tait had asked about parental instinct in various organisms.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Kirby and Spence 1828, 1: 360–1. Earwigs are insects of the order Dermaptera.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">On maternal affection in spiders, see Kirby and Spence 1828, 1: 361–3. CD mentioned parental affection in starfish and spiders in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 106. Starfish are marine invertebrates of the class Asteroidea.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, pp. 106 and 344–6.</note>
        </div>        
            
